abmR: An R Package for Agent-based Model Analysis of Large-scale Movements Across Taxa

Benjamin Gochanour, Javier Fernandez Lopez, Andrea Contina

2021-04-07

library(abmr)

1 Getting Started

1.1 Installation

To use abmR, you must first install it from Github using devtools and load the library:

#devtools: install_github("bgoch5/abmr")
library(abmr,quietly=TRUE,warn.conflicts=FALSE)

While this package is still in development, it will be updated frequently, so please be sure to re-install frequently. Installing abmr will also automaticaly install its dependencies, if you dont already have them installed. These include raster, sp, rgdal, table1, googledrive, swfscMisc, geosphere, kableExtra, and gtsummary.

1.2 Requirements for Environmental Data Rasters and Species objects

The modeling functions discussed below require several input objects to work, which we will discuss here.

1.2.1 Environmental raster stack

Example data that will be used in this Vignette and other package documentation can be downloaded using get_example_data(). This function will download to your hard drive (to a location specified by your current working directory) the below NDVI raster files, totaling approximately 620 MB. The first time you use this function, you will be directed to your browser and required to sign in to your Google account to connect to the Tidyverse API. If you use the function a second time, you may simply follow the prompts and enter a number corresponding to the previous accounts listed.

# get_ex_data() Commented out because can't run in non-interactive RMD session

Once you have the data downloaded, you must read it into R using commands like the following. You may instead use your own environmental raster data - NDVI or otherwise - and read it into R in a similar way.

ndvi_raster_NA=stack("C:\\Users\\BGOCHANOUR\\Documents\\GitHub\\move-model\\NDVI_2013_NA.gri")
ndvi_raster_NA_composite=stack("C:\\Users\\BGOCHANOUR\\Documents\\GitHub\\move-model\\NDVI_2013_NA_composite.gri")
ndvi_raster_EU=stack("C:\\Users\\BGOCHANOUR\\Documents\\GitHub\\move-model\\NDVI_2013_Europe.gri")
ndvi_raster_EU_composite=stack("C:\\Users\\BGOCHANOUR\\Documents\\GitHub\\move-model\\NDVI_2013_Europe_composite.gri")

We can now quickly examine our raster data to see if it read in correctly.

First, we plot the Rasters for North America. The first raster is a 27-layer stack (of which we will plot the first four layers), and the second is a composite raster formed by taking the mean of all layers.

plot(ndvi_raster_NA[[1:4]]) # First four layers of 27 layer RasterStack

plot(ndvi_raster_NA_composite) # This is average of above 27 layer raster

Next, plot the European data.

plot(ndvi_raster_EU[[1:4]]) # First four layers of 27 layer RasterStack

plot(ndvi_raster_EU_composite)

1.2.2 Species object

This object will be constructed with the function as.species, and contains information on origin longitude (x) and latitude (y) as well as two morphological parameters, p1 and p2. Use ?as.species for more details.

Here, we will construct two example species, one for North America and one for Europe.

NA.pop = as.species(x=-98.7, y=34.7, morphpar1=15, morphpar1mean=16,
                      morphpar1sd=2,morphpar1sign="Pos",
                      morphpar2=19,morphpar2mean=18,morphpar2sd=1,morphpar2sign="Pos")

EU.pop = as.species(x=10, y=50, morphpar1=24, morphpar1mean=16,
                        morphpar1sd=5,morphpar1sign="Pos", morphpar2=12, morphpar2mean=9,
                        morphpar2sd=3, morphpar2sign="Neg")

2 Running Agent-based models

abmR has two functions for modeling animal migration: moveSIM and energySIM. Both moveSIM and energySIM will output two things: (1) a dataframe of results ($results) and (2) a summary table of input parameters used ($run_params). For more details on how each function works, please see the documentation by using ?moveSIM or ?energySIM.

We will run moveSIM and energySIM once for each of our species, for a total of four movement simulations.

2.1 moveSIM

First, we will look at moveSIM() the more basic function that.

NA.move=moveSIM(replicates=25,days=27,env_rast=ndvi_raster_NA, search_radius=550,
                sigma=.1, dest_x=-108.6, dest_y=26.2, mot_x=.8,
                mot_y=.8,modeled_species=NA.pop,optimum=.6, n_failures=3, fail_thresh=.40,
                direction="S",write_results=TRUE,single_rast=FALSE,mortality = T)

Simply supply your moveSIM() or energySIM() output and specify type=results or type=run_params, depending on which portion of your output youd like to display.

First, we run this function on our North American moveSIM() output. We will print just the first 35 rows to save space.

3 Visualizing/Summarizing Results

The output from moveSIM and energySIM are simple dataframes, so one may easily visualize their results using custom codes. However, we have provided moveVIZ and energyVIZ, respectively, to provide pre-prepared solutions for visualizing and summarizing your movement simulation results. These functions will be demonstrated first for our North America results and second for our Europe results.

3.1 North American Results

The first two types of output are available for both moveSIM() and energySIM() output via the functions moveVIZ() and energyVIZ(), respectively.

3.1.1 Movement tracks

moveVIZ(NA.move, type="plot", title="moveSIM North America results")

energyVIZ(NA.energy, type="plot", title="EnergySIM North America results")
